caption: Lũ Hiti, first spout, view from W
notes: The stone water-conduit is cladded with copper and is gilded too The hitiphusā (lid of the conduit) has lotus motifs In around 2007

caption: Lũ Hiti, statue of Umāmaheśvara on the top of the spout (LAL1860-001), view from N
notes: Śiva is shown here with four hands One of his right hands holds a rosary whilst the other displays the varada gesture He holds a trident with one of his left hands Their vehicles (vāhana)

caption: Lũ Hiti, middle spout, view from W
notes: The hitipusā (lid of the conduit) has lotus motifs Two Bhagīratha

caption: Lũ Hiti, statue of Viṣṇu on the top of the middle spout (LAL1860-003), view from N
notes: Viṣṇu is holding a wheel and lotus with his two right hands and a club and conch with his two left hands He is surmounted by seven serpent kings (nāga)

caption: Lũ Hiti, statue of Brahmā on the top of the third spout (LAL1860-005 ), view from N
notes: This idol differs from the common idols of Brahmā  He is commonly found with four faces

caption: Lũ Hiti, Śivaliṅga, view from N
Lũ Hiti, statue of Viṣṇu, view from N
notes: Standing Viṣṇu is holding a wheel and lotus on his two right hands and a club and conch on his two left hands The lotus and conch are not clearly visible He is surrounded by seven serpent kings (nāga) Garuḍa is praying to him

caption: Lũ Hiti, Byā̃cā Hiti, view from N
notes: "It is called Byā̃cā Hiti because a frog is placed on its top Water falls down from the mouth of a cow which is joined to the mouth of a crocodile The hitiphusā of the conduit holds a śivaliṅga and an image of a frog The eight auspicious symbols are drawn on the wall and a statue of Bhagīratha is fixed below the conduit In NS 821 the grandsons of King Siddhinarasiṃha Malla

caption: Lũ Hiti, statue of Viṣṇu, view from N
notes: Siting Viṣṇu is holding a conch and wheel on his two right hands and a club and lotus on his two left hands

caption: Lũ Hiti, statue of Varuṇa, view from N
notes: Varuṇa is sitting on a crocodile Generally he holds a conch on his right hand however it is not clear what is holding in this statue He is holding a serpent on his left hand and the seven serpents are capping him

caption: Lũ Hiti, statue of Viṣṇu, view from N

source: Niels Gutschow, Architecture of the Newars, 2011, vol 2, p 649     A stone statue of Lakṣmīnārāyaṇa is enshrined in the sanctum The deities sit on a two-layered lotus pedestal A four-handed Nārāyaṇa sits in an āliḍha posture whilst holding a wheel and a lotus in his right hands and a club in one of his left hands His other left hand holds a conch and is embracing Lakṣmī She is depicted sitting in Nārāyaṇa’s lap, with one foot over a tortoise and one hand performing the gesture of vitarka
